All clean, no leftover files. **TheFloorIsLava.dll v1.1.0** is deployed.

Here's what I changed and why — both bugs were rooted in fragile dependencies that I've now eliminated:

### Damage fix — pure-arithmetic detection
The old detection chained three fragile mechanisms (a kinematic-Rigidbody-trigger + `OnTriggerStay` + `GetComponentInParent<ENT_Player>` + `Physics.OverlapSphere` + `Collider.ClosestPoint`). Any one of them failing silently meant `onLava=false` forever. I replaced all of it with a single, deterministic loop:

```202:243:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
    public bool PlayerOnLava(ENT_Player player, out float nearestHoriz, out int candidates)
    {
        nearestHoriz = float.MaxValue;
        candidates = 0;
        if (_zones.Count == 0)
            return false;

        var touch = _cfg.TouchDistance.Value;
        var vertAbove = _cfg.VerticalAbove.Value;
        var vertBelow = _cfg.VerticalBelow.Value;
        var body = player.transform.position;
        var feet = GameRefs.FeetPosition(player);
```

For every zone: check `feet.y - zp.y` falls inside a wide vertical window (1.8m above / 1m below), then check horizontal distance from `body.xz` against `Radius + TouchDistance`. No physics queries, no triggers, no Rigidbody messages — it cannot silently break.

`SpikeZone` is now a 13-line pure marker (no Rigidbody, no Collider) and `LavaContact.cs` is gone.

### Generation fix — continuous, hook-independent world scan
The old generation relied on `HandholdManager.LoadHandholds` firing per room (with Harmony picking up the `roomRoot` parameter by name — which often resolves to null in stripped IL) and on a 40m radius "explore" scan. Both could miss vertical rooms.

The new `TickWorldScan` runs every 1s independently of any game hook:

```40:74:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
    public void TickWorldScan(ENT_Player player, float dt)
    {
        _worldScanTimer += dt;
        if (_worldScanTimer < _cfg.WorldScanInterval.Value)
            return;
        _worldScanTimer = 0f;
        ScanScene(player);
    }
```

It walks every scene root, checks each collider's bounds-to-player distance (80m horizontal, **60m vertical**), and fills any new floor it finds. `CellKey` is now a pure world-position hash so duplicates can't slip in regardless of which scan path placed them. The `LoadHandholds` hook still fires a `ForceScan` as an early-warning, but generation no longer depends on it.

### Always-on diagnostics
With `DebugLog=true` by default, the BepInEx console now prints once per second:

```
status: onLava=False hp=100 zones=842 candidates=4 nearestH=0.31m feet=(...) body=(...)
```

If you ever see `candidates>0 nearestH<2m onLava=False`, that tells us exactly which threshold to widen. And every second of actual damage prints:

```
LAVA DAMAGE applied: hp=87.5/100 (dps=15.0)
```

So if hp on the bar isn't moving but the log shows damage, we'd know the UI is the problem instead.

Run the game and post the first 30 seconds of `LogOutput.log` if anything still feels off — the new logs make the failure mode unambiguous.

