Built and deployed. **TheFloorIsLava.dll v1.3.2**.

### Why they went invisible, and the two-part fix

**Part 1: the cone mesh was missing UVs and tangents.**
My procedural cone only set `vertices`, `normals`, and `triangles`. URP/Lit and Standard both require:
- **UVs** to sample the texture (without them the texture sampler reads `(0,0)` everywhere or returns nothing depending on shader)
- **Tangents** for the lighting math (without them URP/Lit can output zeros, leaving the surface effectively unlit/invisible)

The rewritten `ConeMesh.Build` now generates each side triangle with its own tip vertex so UVs can wrap without an apex singularity, fills proper UV islands for the side faces and the base cap, and calls `RecalculateTangents()`:

```225:303:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
            for (var i = 0; i < segments; i++)
            {
                var a0 = i / (float)segments * Mathf.PI * 2f;
                var a1 = (i + 1) / (float)segments * Mathf.PI * 2f;
                var c0 = Mathf.Cos(a0); var s0 = Mathf.Sin(a0);
                var c1 = Mathf.Cos(a1); var s1 = Mathf.Sin(a1);

                var baseIdx = i * 3;
                var vTip = baseIdx;
                var vB0 = baseIdx + 1;
                var vB1 = baseIdx + 2;
```

**Part 2: I was cloning the level's full material onto a brand-new mesh.**
Cloning copies every shader keyword the source material had — normal-map keywords, parallax, occlusion, detail maps, etc. Those keywords expect data on the mesh (tangent space, second UV channel, vertex color, etc.) that my cone doesn't have, so the shader returned zero across all faces.

The new sampler **extracts only the texture** from a nearby level renderer, then builds a clean material from a pristine shader picked by trying a fallback chain that matches what's loaded in the game:

```105:128:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
    private static Shader? FindUsableShader(out string name)
    {
        string[] candidates =
        {
            "Universal Render Pipeline/Lit",
            "Universal Render Pipeline/Simple Lit",
            "Universal Render Pipeline/Unlit",
            "Standard",
            "Legacy Shaders/Diffuse",
            "Unlit/Texture",
            "Sprites/Default",
        };
        foreach (var n in candidates)
        {
            var s = Shader.Find(n);
            if (s != null)
            {
                name = n;
                return s;
            }
        }
        name = "";
        return null;
    }
```

The texture is bound through `_BaseMap`, `_MainTex`, `_BaseColorMap`, and `mainTexture` so it works for URP, Built-in, and legacy shaders alike. Tint is applied via both `color` and `_BaseColor` for the same reason. The log line now prints `shader='…' tex='…' source='…' from '…'` so you can confirm which shader and texture were actually used.

