Built clean. **TheFloorIsLava.dll v1.4.0** is deployed.

### Summary of changes

**1. Color matched to the level palette**
Looking at the screenshot — dark charcoal stone with faint warm embers — I tinted the spike material accordingly:

```92:103:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
        var tint = new Color(0.32f, 0.28f, 0.25f, 1f);
        mat.color = tint;
        SetColorIfPresent(mat, "_BaseColor", tint);
        SetColorIfPresent(mat, "_Color", tint);

        if (mat.HasProperty("_Surface")) mat.SetFloat("_Surface", 0f);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_ZWrite")) mat.SetFloat("_ZWrite", 1f);

        // Subtle warm ember emission so the dark spike still reads against shadowed
        // walls without looking like a separate decoration.
        mat.EnableKeyword("_EMISSION");
        SetColorIfPresent(mat, "_EmissionColor", new Color(0.18f, 0.07f, 0.03f, 1f));
```

The level-texture sampling still runs (so spikes get the actual stone texture) but it's now multiplied by a dark charcoal tint with a low-intensity warm-ember emission — they pick up the same gray-with-orange-flecks palette as the wall stone instead of looking like bright beige decorations.

**2. Ground-support check**
A 4-cardinal-direction probe ring around each candidate position. The spike only spawns if at least 3 of 4 probes hit the same target collider within ±35 cm of the center height — overhanging edges and gaps are now rejected.

```67:84:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
    private static bool HasGroundSupport(Vector3 surface, float radius, Collider target)
    {
        var supported = 0;
        for (var i = 0; i < SupportOffsets.Length; i++)
        {
            var origin = surface + SupportOffsets[i] * radius + Vector3.up * 0.35f;
            if (!Physics.Raycast(origin, Vector3.down, out var hit, 0.9f, ~0,
                    QueryTriggerInteraction.Ignore))
                continue;
            if (Mathf.Abs(hit.point.y - surface.y) > 0.35f)
                continue;
            if (!IsHitOnCollider(hit, target))
                continue;
            supported++;
        }
        return supported >= 3;
    }
```

**3. Per-spike noise — every cone is unique**
Each spike now gets a deterministic seed hashed from its world position, then random yaw (0–360°), random tilt (default ±14°), and random scale (default ±25%). Deterministic means rescans always produce the same cone at the same position, so you don't see them "wobble" if a room re-scans.

```114:127:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
        var seed = HashPosition(pos);
        var rng = new System.Random(seed);
        var yaw = (float)rng.NextDouble() * 360f;
        var tiltDeg = (float)(rng.NextDouble() * _cfg.SpikeTiltDegrees.Value);
        var tiltDir = (float)rng.NextDouble() * 360f;
        var scaleNoise = (float)(rng.NextDouble() * 2.0 - 1.0); // -1 .. 1
        var scaleMul = 1f + scaleNoise * _cfg.SpikeScaleJitter.Value;

        var baseRot = Quaternion.FromToRotation(Vector3.up, n);
        var yawRot = Quaternion.AngleAxis(yaw, Vector3.up);
        var tiltAxis = new Vector3(Mathf.Cos(tiltDir * Mathf.Deg2Rad), 0f, Mathf.Sin(tiltDir * Mathf.Deg2Rad));
        var tiltRot = Quaternion.AngleAxis(tiltDeg, tiltAxis);
        go.transform.rotation = baseRot * tiltRot * yawRot;
```

**4. Smooth noise-scatter across each surface**
The 4-cone cluster is gone — each zone is now one larger, dominant cone. Placement uses a denser jittered grid (step = 45% of spacing) and modulates spawn probability with Perlin noise so spikes form natural patches of higher and lower density across each continuous floor instead of grid-like cells:

```46:69:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\Spikes\SpikeField.cs
        for (var x = bounds.min.x; x <= bounds.max.x + 0.01f; x += step)
        {
            for (var z = bounds.min.z; z <= bounds.max.z + 0.01f; z += step)
            {
                if (_zones.Count >= cap)
                    return;

                // Density modulation: Perlin patches of denser and sparser spikes.
                var density = Mathf.PerlinNoise(x * noiseScale, z * noiseScale);
                if (density < minDensity)
                    continue;

                // Jitter the probe inside the cell using two decorrelated noise samples.
                var jx = (Mathf.PerlinNoise(x * 1.7f + 13.1f, z * 1.7f) - 0.5f) * 2f * jitter;
                var jz = (Mathf.PerlinNoise(x * 1.7f, z * 1.7f + 27.9f) - 0.5f) * 2f * jitter;
```

All four behaviors are user-tunable via the new `[Lava]` entries:

```
