content.text:
Deployed. Here's what changed about the visible tablet:

**Two solid emissive cubes, no texture**

The previous tablet was a single textured cube. URP/Unlit's plain-opaque variant (no `_ALPHATEST_ON`) is apparently stripped from this build's shaders, so any path that wasn't alpha-tested was falling back to black. The fix mirrors the lava-base material exactly — alpha-tested URP/Unlit opaque with `_ALPHATEST_ON`, `_AlphaClip=1`, `_Cutoff=0.05` — which is the same recipe the lava patches use and renders correctly. Since `_BaseColor.a = 1`, every fragment passes the cutoff and the cube renders as a solid colour.

```338:365:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\EasterEgg.cs
        // Match the lava base material EXACTLY: alpha-tested URP/Unlit opaque.
        // Even though we have no texture, this is the shader variant that this
        // build actually compiles/renders — the plain "Opaque" variant
        // (_AlphaClip=0, no _ALPHATEST_ON keyword) seems to be stripped and
        // falls back to black. Since _BaseColor.a is 1, every fragment passes
        // the alpha cutoff, so the cube renders as a solid emissive colour.
        if (mat.HasProperty("_Surface")) mat.SetFloat("_Surface", 0f);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_Blend")) mat.SetFloat("_Blend", 0f);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_SrcBlend")) mat.SetFloat("_SrcBlend", (float)UnityEngine.Rendering.BlendMode.One);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_DstBlend")) mat.SetFloat("_DstBlend", (float)UnityEngine.Rendering.BlendMode.Zero);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_ZWrite")) mat.SetFloat("_ZWrite", 1f);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_Cull")) mat.SetFloat("_Cull", 2f);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_AlphaClip")) mat.SetFloat("_AlphaClip", 1f);
        if (mat.HasProperty("_Cutoff")) mat.SetFloat("_Cutoff", 0.05f);
        mat.EnableKeyword("_ALPHATEST_ON");
        mat.DisableKeyword("_SURFACE_TYPE_TRANSPARENT");
        mat.DisableKeyword("_ALPHABLEND_ON");
        mat.renderQueue = (int)UnityEngine.Rendering.RenderQueue.AlphaTest;
```

**Emission for guaranteed visibility**

Both materials get `_EmissionColor = color × strength` (1.0× white border, 2.0× red fill) and `_EMISSION` is enabled. The cubes are self-illuminated, so they're bright even sitting in a dark patch of floor away from the lava glow.

**3× longer + white frame around red bar**

Layout (two stacked cubes, centred at origin):

```256:288:c:\Users\TFS\Documents\projects\White Knuckle Mod\SpikeBalanceMod\EasterEgg.cs
        // Outer white "border" slab.
        var border = GameObject.CreatePrimitive(PrimitiveType.Cube);
        Object.Destroy(border.GetComponent<Collider>());
        border.name = "Border";
        border.transform.SetParent(root.transform, false);
        border.transform.localScale = new Vector3(TabletLength, TabletThickness, TabletDepth);
        border.transform.localPosition = Vector3.zero;
        ConfigureRenderer(border.GetComponent<MeshRenderer>(),
            BuildEmissiveSolid(new Color(0.96f, 0.96f, 0.96f, 1f), 1.0f, "Border"));

        // Red "fill" — slightly larger in Y (so it pokes above/below the
        // white slab, showing red on the long faces), slightly smaller in
        // X+Z (so the white border is visible around it from top/bottom).
        var fill = GameObject.CreatePrimitive(PrimitiveType.Cube);
        Object.Destroy(fill.GetComponent<Collider>());
        fill.name = "Fill";
        fill.transform.SetParent(root.transform, false);
        fill.transform.localScale = new Vector3(
            TabletLength - 0.06f,
            TabletThickness + 0.02f,
            TabletDepth - 0.03f);
```

- White border slab: **1.50 × 0.05 × 0.12 m** (3.3× longer than before).
- Red fill: **1.44 × 0.07 × 0.09 m** — slightly *taller* in Y so the red pokes above and below the white slab (showing red on the long faces), slightly *narrower* in X and Z so the white shows as a frame from the top/bottom.

So when the tablet lands on the floor — the most common viewing angle — you'll see red bar in a white frame. From the long sides, you see the white slab with a red strip sticking out top and bottom. The collider matches the outer white dimensions, and mass is bumped to 0.6 kg so it doesn't fly off when nudged.

Material build logs are now per-material with shader name, colour, and emission value, so if anything still looks wrong I can pinpoint which cube failed and which shader Unity ended up choosing.

